{"key":"processedPost-10998039","value":{"id":10998039,"first":10996343,"last":10998212,"when":1252081207,"utime":"09/04/09 07:20 PM","content":"Yes, cakes can be misted directly.&nbsp; In the early days it was thought it took a sealed up terrarium to maintain humidity.&nbsp; They also had poor to mediocre performance back then.&nbsp; We now know that fresh air exchange is a major pinning trigger, and that you can mist cakes directly as long as they don't sit there wet in still and stale air.&nbsp; In fact, you NEED to mist your substrates to replace the moisture that evaporates, which is another major pinning trigger.&nbsp; We've come a long way in knowledge of mushroom cultivation in the last dozen years or so.<br /><br />To answer your question, drip shields are not needed, and in fact counterproductive.<br />RR","title":"Re: Shotgun drip shield","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}